comments.text: It took me three or four tries to get this right.  I've been using blue tape on my print bed, to make it easier to remove my prints.  When I printed this at 230 degrees with PLA on the Replicator 2, the corners kept lifting up, eventually causing the print to fail each time.  I messed with different infills, but once I eliminated the blue tape on the bed, it stuck better, and I got a perfect print.  Another tip:  print the first 80% in one color, and then do a cold pause, and switch to another color filament that has high contrast from the first color.  (I've started with white and then switched to blue).  It will make the text much easier to read - and it looks WAY-cool!  I'm sorry to not show the one that I made, but I'd rather not publish all of my personal information on the Thingiverse if I can help it.

description.text:
This is a knurled knob that will fit on the nut holding the Z Axis on an Xcarve upgrade of a ShapeOko2. The nut is an M6 so it should fit both the standard lead screw implementation or the ACME screw. In my case I upgraded my ShapeOko2 to an Xcarve with an ACME screw on the Z Axis.

This is not a difficult piece but I wanted to learn how to knurl the surface in Fusion 360. I am happy how it came out on the first try so I though I would share.

Printed with a .4mm nozzle using basic settings at 10% on a Rostock Vmax 2.

We bought a very nice steel bunk bed for my son,
But, although the frame is nice and strong, the bars, that the mattress rests on

A simple woodworking micro lathe, powered by a Dremel. The goal is to design a simple lathe with few moving parts. Will mostly be used for making parts for my model aircrafts.

Materials:
1 set of printed parts
2 steel rods 10mm x 600mm
1 steel rod 10mm x 40mm
1 theaded steel rod 10mm x 600mm
2-3 M10 nuts
1 M10 washer
9 M4 nuts
9 socket head screw M4x25mm
1 bearing 15x35x8mm (for moving tail stock)

Instructions:
-Print one piece of every stl-file. You might have to adjust the holes in order to make the rods fit.

-Cut the long rods at the desired length.

-Solder a M10 nut on the end of the threaded rod. (or mount two nuts on the threaded rod and fasten them against each other.) Make a cut in the other end with a saw.

-Mount the short (40mm) rod in a drilling machine and sharpen one end with a rasp.
Put the rod with the flat end first into the tail stock. This rod works as the dead center.

-Mount all nuts in their slots and place the socket head screws into them.

-Insert all three rods into the head socket, compound rest and tail socket.

-Glue the engine mount into the head socket.

-Forge av sharpen a round nail to make a fastener.

description.text:
Update 11/3/2016
I added 3 more options to use this with 1/2" EMT (Electrical Metal Tubing), 3/4"EMT or 1/2" PVC so I can use this on an Emmett-Delta.

This is a customizable base for the Universal stand-alone filament spool holder http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:508896

Since I had already done most of the work to make this customizable for 2020 aluminum, I went further and made it customizable for the 6 different extrusions. By changing a few variables in the openscad script, you should be able to customize this for many other sizes.

There are 2 different profiles for the spool spindle shaft, original & new defined with the variable OriginalCenter set to 0 or 1. If you are using this with original spindles, you will want to set that to 0. I included Spool_Original_Spindle_And_Shaft_Test.stl & Spool_New_Spindle_And_Shaft_Test.stl so you can test how each version of the shaft fits the spindle without wasting a lot of plastic.

I have only tested the 2020 version of this, but included test prints for how the aluminum 1515, 2020, 2525, 3030, 4020, or 4040 fits. Since there are so many possible combinations, I did not include STL files for any of the final parts. See http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1715713 for more info on changes I made to this design. A customizable version of the Filament guide tube can be found here: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1710043

If you need help with understanding some of these variables, let me know.

description.text:
ABS and PLA are not stronger than properly glued plywood unless they are substantially thicker and heavier. So, since there is no need to design and print the wood center structure I have created this simple Gear Deck that fits the stock structure of the Mini Talon perfectly. There are four deck clips which are threaded for a 3mm x 10mm stand-off and a deck piece which has a pile of slots and holes for passing wires and/or wire ties. A complete set-up includes:

1x Gear_Deck_v1.stl
2x Gear_Deck_Clip_v2.stl
2x Gear_Deck_Clip_Mirror_v2.stl
4x M3 x 6mm Screws
4x 3mm Flat washers
4x M3 x 10mm nylon Stand-offs

After all pieces are printed, cleaned up and the four clips tapped, assemble th deck in the plane without the stand-offs and keep the screws loose. Add a little glue to each clip where it contacts the wood then gently tighten all four screws making sure all pieces stay straight and square. Let the glue set-up then it is ready to load up with your gear and add the stan-offs!

Note: If you desire a cushioned deck simply replace the nylon stand-offs with rubber anti-vibration stand-offs.

To see my build pages on this project, please visit:
http://www.itsqv.com/QVM/index.php?title=Mini_Talon_X-UAV_Build_Number_2

title: Geeetech i3 Pro C inductive sensor mount

description.text:
Update Nov 4, 2017 I have now added a 3dTouch version of this mount. Check it out!
"3dTouch sensor Mount Geeetech I3 Pro C(B) mounting"

Inductive sensor mount for Geeetech prusa i3 Pro C
The mount uses the existing top X axis mount screws. Mounts on the rear of the X axis and rests on the top bearing.

New Photo added. Shown without aluminum foil under the glass - not needed anymore.

If you print this, please post a picture on the 'I've made one'. Thanks!

Problems getting auto level working

First, I had the wrong sign on the offset. This caused havoc in the centering, auto leveling and Slic3r. Should have been -51 not 53 (remeasured and found it to be 51mm.)

Secondly, comes the confusing part of bed_position verses offset. Yes, they interact with each other. I have made notes on how it calculates the position. I hope this helps.
this took the longest time (hours) as every change I had to upload the new changed firmware moving only one point at a time to see what changed. Then I used the following codes the most to help in troubleshooting

G28 X0 Y0 ; Home X and Y only to the stops. This prevents homing to the center.
G29; auto level command.
M114; to print out current printer position. (Repetier-Host also echos the position in the bottom window)
G1 ?; where ? = axis to move, and = to what positon. (example G1 X50 moves X axis to 50)
Software using; Repetier-Host V1.6.2 to enter G codes manually and to have the cursor over the Emergency Stop - just in case (used many times)

After tweeking the numbers for the offset, and probe_bed_positions I finally had the auto level going to the positions I wanted. But a G28 (home) sent the extruder to the center and beyond the back of the printing bed.

3rd correction; I found Z_safe_homing. and tried subtracting from the safe_homing_Y-Point. It worked! With some tweeking I settled on -20 in the X and -100 in the Y.
First print with the new set up. Centered in the bed, Slic3r works perfectly.
Designed in Freecad. Printed on the side. Designed to use the exiting mounting for the x axis so it is centered on the dual extruders.

Marlin Firmware settings Probing points

LEFT_PROBE_BED_POSITION 5 // left position 21, left probe bed positon - (x probe offset from extruder)
RIGHT_PROBE_BED_POSITION 155 // right position 171, right probe bed positon - (x probe offset from extruder)
BACK_PROBE_BED_POSITION 66 // back positon 117, back probe bed positon - (y probe offset from extruder)
FRONT_PROBE_BED_POSITION -51 // front position 0, Front probe bed position - (y probe offset from extruder)

Marlin Firmware settings probe offsets

X_PROBE_OFFSET_FROM_EXTRUDER -16 // offset from left extruder
Y_PROBE_OFFSET_FROM_EXTRUDER -51 // offset from centerline of both extruders
Z_PROBE_OFFSET_FROM_EXTRUDER -1.6

Marlin Firmware settings Safe Homing positions

SAFE_HOMING_X_POINT (X_MAX_LENGTH/2-20) // X point for Z homing when homing all axis (G28) // -20 added
Z_SAFE_HOMING_Y_POINT (Y_MAX_LENGTH/2-100) // Y point for Z homing when homing all axis (G28) //-100 added

Next step: Things I've learned

While this sensor mount works, the sensor is a bit far away from the extruder. This prevents doing a 9 point auto level. I'm looking at ways to redesign it. It will be similar to this one.
I also believe the extruder can be mounted closer to the centerline of the axis. (drilling holes closer will do it). These two 'updates' should allow for a closer spacing and possibly 9 point auto level.

I also found that my glass plate was being warped by the clamps, wires and aluminum foil.
Corrections. I flipped the heating bed over (not how any pictures I have seen from Geeetech).
Then I made some great glass clips. Kudos to the author (I'll take pictures later and officially thank them). doing this has allowed me to get rid of the aluminum foil, as the 8mm sensor can now sense the heating bed! And the clips mean I have a full bed to print on now - nothing to run into.

I hope this posting gives you the information that you need to get your auto level operating.

Next step: Things I've learned ... continued

My glass bed is just not level. If I try to level with the leveling knobs, it seems to warp from opposite corners. The fix for now - is to not have the bed perfectly level and use the leveling knows to keep the glass plate from warping. This caused the z axis to correct about 1/2 a turn from the front to the back but it seems to be working well.

I have taken the printer apart and verified that the x-y mounting plate is perpendicular to the z axis and close to level in all positions. It is just when the glass plate get attached things go haywire and the glass plate warps. Could be a bad glass plate? Research shows others have that problem. Change to metal? I haven't had much problem with my prints coming off the glass. I hear a lot of problems with metal plates.

For now, I think I will be ok with the 'having to not level fully' and just have the auto level correct for any flaws.

Hope this helps

title: Alunar Prusa i3 (A8) Frame Mounted Spool Holder

description.text:
Couldn't find a frame-mounted spool holder for the Alunar 3D printer, so I designed one.

The mounts clamp on without the need of any extra hardware. Need to really clean up the edges and corners on the dovetail joints to get them to fit, but once you do, the spool holder is surprisingly sturdy.

Matching accessories:
Spacers: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1752025
MicroSD Holder: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1752205
Tool Holder: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1752265

Printer:

Alunar Prusa i3 (A8)

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

Cura 2.1 Default - Low Quality

Infill:

10%

Explanation of Design

This is designed to fit on the Alunar print bed. Uses a dovetail joint that works really well if you clean up the corners; I use a flat-head screwdriver to smooth it down the edges and corners. It's a snug fit. The frame mounts need to be forced on, but they clamp on really tight. It makes for a shockingly sturdy spool holder.

In Cura, you can mirror the object. If you use the original file and the horizontal mirror, you can fit both of them on the same print. At low-quality with a 10% infill, it takes about 4.5 hours to print both of them together.

title: Pull switch for automotive use (brake switch, kickdown swith etc.)
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This is a switch i mostly designed to use as a kickdown switch.
Key item in this is the safety door switch or microwave door switch as they are often called.

The black design is the most recent one, it uses one door switch, two springs to keep the trigger in when youre not pulling it and the 3 pcs M3x15mm screws (18mm is maximum unless you want is coming out on the other side). This will release the switch when the trigger moves 1,5-2mm out and the trigger can then move another 8-9mm out. I would suggest connecting it with a harder spring if you need more movement after it reaches its maximum stretch point. The switch usually have both NC and NO connections.

The grey one is the initial design wich i included but kind of abandoned. I also included some linkage for it, maybe someone have use for it.

title: Spring Bed Clip for Round Print Beds (Kossel, Rostock)

description.text:
There are multiple designs to choose from. For the Kossel Mini I found I needed to recess the top to allow clearance for the hot end. The designs are in order of my preference, and I would advise printing one before printing all three and doing a test fit between the X and Y towers. This is the area with the least amount of clearance when autoleveling. The print bed inset_multiplier determines the depth the curve is cut into the clip. The idea is to slide the bed into the curved void, use the two holes on the corners to hold it more firmly if you have a loose fit. A hex head bolt (m3) is slid into the track of v-slot and tightened into place with a nut. A very strong spring is fitted over this and the bed clip slides over the bolt. You adjust the height with a nut placed over the clip.
I'd advise tightening it down a few turns before starting to allow for loosening if needed. Highly customizable. You need all scad files to edit parameters. Using a lock nut would probably be advised. This would probably work great without springs too!

Can be printed in two seperate prints or in one go with edits.

Assembly

  1. Print

  2. Size all the holes according to whatever rod you use, I used 1.75mm filament

  3. Acetone weld the three C's into one piece on top of one another with the L in the corner without holes in the middle of the larger ones making sure to line up the holes.

  4. Glue the small 4mm thick line shaped piece between the two C's in the top gap

  5. glue the wider L shaped piece to the flat piece both of which are from the internal piece group with two holes each making sure to line up the holes.

  6. Use the rod to connect the holes in the C's to the rounded rectangles.

  7. Connect via the holes with rod the two rounded rectangles to the piece you made in step 5 sanding to ensure a smooth fit.

  8. Glue the long 12 mm tall piece to a long edge of the 100mm by 50mm rectangle using solvent welding.

  9. Glue the two C's to the opposite long edge on the same side of the large rectangle being careful not to glue the piece you attached in step 7.

Modified version of the original Robo R1 wades style extruder. Made to fit the E3d V6 .4.2mm hole for PTFE tube as well as 7mmx3mm deep countersink. Robo/E3d logo added. Also added a ziplock mount to hold wiring harness.

Printer Brand: Robo 3D
Printer: R1 ABS + PLA Model
Rafts: No
Supports: Yes
Resolution: Printed at .2mm

Notes:
I printed with 35% infill with PLA and also with PETG but you can print what you like. Make sure you add supports where needed. title: Death Watch Mandalorian Gauntlets Mark 3 with Integrated Hinge.

description.text:
Death Watch Mandalorian Gauntlets MARK3 (Male) with Integrated Hinge.

They are a mirror image of the Bo Katan and a close match to the gauntlets used by most male deathwatch in Star Wars the clone wars season 5

The hinge has been designed to use a common bicycle spoke as the hinge pin. You can buy these from bike shops for $2 and cut to size.

The model has been modified from the previous versions to be printed on larger format printers in one piece, there are also some minor changes to the model mostly to make it more durable

If you would like to watch a video on how to finish these once printed to MMCC standards go here: https://youtu.be/fusLep_OiKg

If you dont have a printer and would like me to print you a new version of this gauntlet, go here: http://www.stormprops.com

A magnetic Thumbs Up! I use it for the dishwasher to indicate clean or dirty dishes or just as a fridge magnet. Many uses of course.

I used ColorPrint by Prusa3d to do the color layer change automatically. (Almost automatic anyway) :). http://prusaprinters.org/color-print/
